Personal Loan Purchase Prediction

Problem Statement¶

Context¶

AllLife Bank is a US bank that has a growing customer base. The majority of these customers are liability customers (depositors) with varying sizes of deposits. The number of customers who are also borrowers (asset customers) is quite small, and the bank is interested in expanding this base rapidly to bring in more loan business and in the process, earn more through the interest on loans. In particular, the management wants to explore ways of converting its liability customers to personal loan customers (while retaining them as depositors).

A campaign that the bank ran last year for liability customers showed a healthy conversion rate of over 9% success. This has encouraged the retail marketing department to devise campaigns with better target marketing to increase the success ratio.

You as a Data scientist at AllLife bank have to build a model that will help the marketing department to identify the potential customers who have a higher probability of purchasing the loan.

Objective¶

To predict whether a liability customer will buy personal loans, to understand which customer attributes are most significant in driving purchases, and identify which segment of customers to target more.

Data Dictionary¶

  • ID: Customer ID
  • Age: Customers age in completed years
  • Experience: #years of professional experience
  • Income: Annual income of the customer (in thousand dollars)
  • ZIP Code: Home Address ZIP code.
  • Family: the Family size of the customer
  • CCAvg: Average spending on credit cards per month (in thousand dollars)
  • Education: Education Level. 1: Undergrad; 2: Graduate;3: Advanced/Professional
  • Mortgage: Value of house mortgage if any. (in thousand dollars)
  • Personal_Loan: Did this customer accept the personal loan offered in the last campaign? (0: No, 1: Yes)
  • Securities_Account: Does the customer have securities account with the bank? (0: No, 1: Yes)
  • CD_Account: Does the customer have a certificate of deposit (CD) account with the bank? (0: No, 1: Yes)
  • Online: Do customers use internet banking facilities? (0: No, 1: Yes)
  • CreditCard: Does the customer use a credit card issued by any other Bank (excluding All life Bank)? (0: No, 1: Yes)

Data Types:¶

All columns are either int64 or float64 → numeric by Pandas, but semantically some are categorical.¶

Continuous / Numerical Features :¶

  • Age (int) continuous, but bounded (valid human age range).

  • Experience (int) continuous, but needs to be consistent with Age.

  • Income (int) continuous, measured in $000s.

  • CCAvg (float) continuous, average monthly spend ($000s).

  • Mortgage (int) continuous, measured in $000s.

Categorical (though stored as int64) :¶

  • Family discrete, valid range should be 1-4.

  • Education encoded as 1: Undergrad, 2: Graduate, 3: Professional.

  • Securities_Account, CD_Account, Online, CreditCard binary (0/1).

  • Personal_Loan target variable, binary (0/1).

Identifiers / Not Predictive :¶

  • ID unique identifier, should be dropped from modeling.

  • ZIPCode categorical-like, but too granular; usually dropped unless aggregated to regions.

Demographics :¶

  • Customers are mostly middle-aged: Age ranges 23-67, median ~45 years.

  • Experience averages ~20 years, but min is -3 (invalid) requires correction.

Financial Profile :¶

  • Income: Wide spread, avg ~73k dollars, median 64k dollars, with high earners up to $224k.

  • Mortgage: Highly skewed half the customers have 0 mortgage, while some go as high as $635k.

  • Credit Card Spend (CCAvg): Median ~1.5k dollar/month, but heavy spenders reach 10k dollar .

Family & Education :¶

  • Family size ranges 1-4, average ~2.4.

  • Education: Balanced distribution Undergrad (1), Graduate (2), Professional (3); all values within valid range.

Banking Behavior :¶

  • Online banking usage is common (60% use it).

  • Credit card ownership (from other banks) is 29%.

  • Fewer hold Securities (10%) or CD accounts (6%), indicating cross-sell opportunities.

Target Variable (Personal Loan) :¶

  • Only 9.6% customers accepted loans confirms class imbalance.

Check for Anomalies :

  1. Age vs. Experience :

  • Example: Row with Age=26, Experience=1,it is valid.

  • Example: Row with Age=65, Experience=41, it is valid (started work ~24).

  • No negative values here, but in the full dataset I saw -3 years min.

  • Action: Replace negatives with median/age-based correction.
  1. Family :
  • Values: 1, 2, 3, 4 all within expected range.
  • No anomaly.
  1. Education :
  • Values: 1, 2, 3 valid categories (Undergrad, Graduate, Professional).
  • No anomaly.
  1. CCAvg (Credit Card Spend) :
  • Ranges here: 0.1 to 7.9 (all within 0-10 max).
  • very skewed distribution in full dataset (long tail).
  • Action: Apply log-transform or winsorization if used in linear models.
  1. Mortgage :
  • Some have 0, others high (442, 327, 301).
  • No negatives, so it is valid.
  • Action:highly skewed overall dataset, needs scaling/transform.
  1. Banking Behavior (binary flags) :
  • All 0/1 valid.
  1. Personal_Loan (target) :
  • Only 0/1 valid.

Inferences¶

  1. Education

Undergrad: ~2096

Graduate: ~1403

PostGrad: ~1501

Most customers are Undergraduates, but loan acceptance increases with higher education.

  1. Personal_Loan (Target)

Accepted: 9.6% (~480 customers)

Not Accepted: 90.4%

Highly imbalanced target variable, so need to handle imbalance (SMOTE/weights).

  1. Securities_Account

Yes: ~10%

No: ~90%

Very few customers have securities accounts may not be a strong predictor.

  1. CD_Account

Yes: ~6%

No: ~94%

Rare category, but in banking datasets CD account holders often have a higher chance of taking loans.

  1. Online (Internet Banking)

Yes: ~60%

No: ~40%

Majority use online banking can be correlated with loan behavior.

  1. CreditCard

Yes: ~29%

No: ~71%

Most customers don't use external credit cards, but credit usage could indicate loan affinity.

  1. ZIPCode

467 unique categories, each with small counts.

Not useful as-is (too many categories). Better to map to State/Region.

# confusion_matrix_sklearn
def confusion_matrix_sklearn(model, predictors, target):
    """Plot confusion matrix for classification model"""
    predictions = model.predict(predictors)
    cm = confusion_matrix(target, predictions)

    plt.figure(figsize=(5,4))
    sns.heatmap(cm, annot=True, fmt="d", cmap="Blues",
                xticklabels=[0,1], yticklabels=[0,1])
    plt.xlabel("Predicted")
    plt.ylabel("Actual")
    plt.title("Confusion Matrix")
    plt.show()
    print("=== Test Data Performance ===")
confusion_matrix_sklearn(model0, X_test, y_test)

def model_performance_classification_sklearn(model, predictors, target):
    """Return Accuracy, Precision, Recall, and F1 Score as a dictionary"""
    predictions = model.predict(predictors)

    acc = accuracy_score(target, predictions)
    prec = precision_score(target, predictions)
    rec = recall_score(target, predictions)
    f1 = f1_score(target, predictions)

    return {
        "Accuracy": round(acc, 4),
        "Precision": round(prec, 4),
        "Recall": round(rec, 4),
        "F1 Score": round(f1, 4)
    }

Test Performance Drop

Precision/Recall also dropped on test.

This confirms the tree doesn't generalize as well as it memorizes.

Variance Gap

Difference between train and test accuracy = ~2-3% gap.

Not extremely large, but combined with perfect train accuracy indicates overfitting.

In [312]:
# --- Function to calculate performance ---
def model_performance_classification_sklearn(model, predictors, target):
    predictions = model.predict(predictors)
    performance = {
        "Accuracy": accuracy_score(target, predictions),
        "Precision": precision_score(target, predictions),
        "Recall": recall_score(target, predictions),
        "F1 Score": f1_score(target, predictions),
    }
    return performance


model1 = DecisionTreeClassifier(
    random_state=1,
    max_depth=5,          # restrict tree depth
    min_samples_leaf=50   # minimum samples per leaf
)

# Train the model
model1.fit(X_train, y_train)

# Train set performance
print("=== Train Data Performance (Pre-pruned) ===")
decision_tree_pruned_perf_train = model_performance_classification_sklearn(
    model1, X_train, y_train
)
print(decision_tree_pruned_perf_train)

# Test set performance
print("\n=== Test Data Performance (Pre-pruned) ===")
decision_tree_pruned_perf_test = model_performance_classification_sklearn(
    model1, X_test, y_test
)
print(decision_tree_pruned_perf_test)

Overfitting Reduced

  • Since our objective is loan prediction, recall is very important (better to identify as many potential loan customers as possible, even if a few false positives slip in).

But business also wants precision (not waste offers on people unlikely to accept).

That means I need a balanced model with good recall & precision, and not just accuracy. so I select the Pre-pruned Decision Tree (max_depth, min_samples_leaf) as my final model.

It avoids overfitting.

Maintains strong recall (0.85) and good precision (0.90).

Interpretable (bank managers can understand splits).

Actionable Insights and Business Recommendations¶

Actionable Insights¶

  1. Income & Spending (CCAvg) Drive Loan Acceptance

Customers with higher income and higher average credit card spending (CCAvg) show a significantly higher likelihood of accepting personal loans.

Example: Income > 80k and CCAvg > 2.5 strongly correlate with loan acceptance.

  1. Education Matters

Graduates and Postgraduates are more likely to accept loans than Undergraduates.

Advanced education levels also correspond with higher income better target group.

  1. Family Size Influence

Customers from larger families (34 members) show a slightly higher probability of loan acceptance compared to single-member households.

  1. Cross-Selling Opportunities

Customers already having a Securities or CD Account show higher likelihood of accepting loans.

Indicates potential for bundled financial product offerings.

  1. Digital Adoption (Online & Credit Card Users)

Customers who are active online banking users and credit card holders are more likely to engage with new financial products.

Business Recommendations¶

  1. Targeted Marketing Campaigns

Focus campaigns on high-income, high-spending (CCAvg) segments.

Use personalized offers for Graduates/Postgraduates with family responsibilities.

  1. Cross-Sell with Existing Products

Bundle personal loan offers with Securities/CD accounts.

Offer preferential loan terms for customers with multiple products.

  1. Leverage Digital Channels

Prioritize online banking and credit card users for digital marketing campaigns.

Push pre-approved loan offers through mobile apps and internet banking.

  1. Reduce False Positives

Instead of targeting all customers, focus on the profiles identified by the pre-pruned decision tree to improve campaign ROI.

  1. Customer Education Programs

Since education level impacts loan uptake, design financial literacy programs for undergraduates to increase awareness and future loan adoption.
